abstract: Gold is going abroad more largely than anybody in Wall Street has foreseen. Over $1,000,000 per day has been the average export engagement during the week just closed. Any measuring figures, however, depend upon guesswork.

abstract: Animals which loved the cold and those of a torrid land were curiously mingled. Troops of mastodons wandered over the land and gorged themselves on the soft twigs of spruce and fir. In Cannon's "Historical Records of the Twenty-third Regiment," printed in 1847, there is a plate showing a group containing an officer whose back is turned to the spectator, thus affording a good view of the "flash" as then worn.

abstract: New York won yesterday afternoon at the Polo Grounds the third and last game of the opening intercity series against Brooklyn. Their work was marked by none of the errors and misplays that characterized it in Friday's contest.

abstract: The golfing members of Ardsley Casino, on the Hudson, above Dobbs Ferry, held their second Saturday handicap yesterday for Class A and Class B players. abstract: The war in the Levant has evidently wrought great changes. Before it broke out, Turkey was in the hands of the powers, and Greece was acting upon her own account. Now that Greece has been beaten, she has been induced to put herself into the hands of the powers unreservedly. But now it is Turkey which takes airs of independence, and discloses an intention of using her victory to suit herself.

abstract: A great many proofs, now more or less familiar to most people, show quite clearly that the decay of animal or vegetable matter is not a simple chemical change, inevitable in the nature of things, but a violent interference with the natural course on the part of hostile organisms. The bacteria which produce decomposition are very minute plants, which grow, like mushrooms, or molds, upon organic matter, and which reproduce their like with incredible rapidity.

abstract: MORRISTOWN, N.J., May 22. -- The new Republican Common Council was organized last night. City Clerk Ayres, in calling the roll, omitted the name of Alderman Reed, from the Second Ward. abstract: WORCESTER, Mass., May 23. -- The eleventh annual games of the New England Intercollegiate Athletic Association took place at Worcester Oval yesterday in the presence of about 1,500 spectators. Dartmouth won the championship for the third successive year. The scores were: Dartmouth, 29; Brown, 26; Bowdoin, 19; Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 11 1/2; Wesleyan, 11; Amherst, 9; Williams, 7; Trinity, 5 1/2; Tufts, 5; Worcester Polytechnic Institute, 3.

abstract: The situation in Cuba to-day is perfectly clear and simple. In the western provinces we find between 300,000 and 400,000 people penned up in starvation stations, and a prey to all kinds of epidemic disease. They are without means and without food, and with only the shelter that the dried palm leaves of their hastily erected bohios afford, and in the rainy season that is now upon them that is no shelter at all.

abstract: The sacred thread of the Brahmins is well known; it is a caste distinction assumed at an early age, and never parted with. It must be made by a Brahmin, and should consist of three strands, each of a different color, forty-eight yards in length, doubled and twisted together twice, the ends tied in knots. It must be worn next the skin, over the left shoulder, hanging down to the thigh on the right side.

abstract: DUCK LAKE, N.W.T., May 30. -- The transport party which left for the scene of the Indian trouble at 6:15 this morning reports that Capt. Gagnon, with a seven-pounder field gun, arrived at the bluff where the Indians are intrenched, before dark last night, and fired seven shells into the bluff. At dusk, when everything had quieted down, Almighty Voice yelled to the police that they were doing well, but would have to do better.
